To ensure that code from the develop branch cannot be merged into main if the DevSecOps pipeline fails, you must configure Branch Protection Rules in GitHub. This works together with your CI pipeline in GitHub Actions.

Below is the standard enterprise approach.

  1. Concept

When a developer creates a Pull Request:

develop  →  main

GitHub will:

Run the GitHub Actions pipeline

Check the job results

Block the merge if any job fails

Example pipeline stages:

Secret Scan
SAST Scan
Dependency Scan
Policy Check
Frontend Build
Backend Build

If any stage fails → Merge button is disabled.

2. Enable Branch Protection for main

Go to your repository.

Repository → Settings → Branches

Click:

Add Branch Protection Rule

Branch name pattern:

main
3. Enable Required Status Checks

Enable:

Require status checks to pass before merging

Then select the pipeline jobs.

Example:

secret-scan
sast-scan
dependency-scan
policy-check
frontend-build
backend-build

Now GitHub requires all checks to pass.

4. Require Pull Request

Enable:

Require a pull request before merging

This prevents direct pushes to main.

Workflow becomes:

Developer → develop branch
        │
        ▼
Create Pull Request
        │
        ▼
GitHub Actions Pipeline
        │
        ▼
Checks Pass → Merge Allowed
Checks Fail → Merge Blocked
5. Require Review (Recommended)

Enable:

Require approvals

Example:

1 approval required

This creates a governance gate.

6. Prevent Bypass

Enable:

Do not allow bypassing the above settings

Even admins cannot merge failing builds.

7. Example Real DevSecOps Flow
Developer commits code
        │
        ▼
Push to develop branch
        │
        ▼
Pull Request: develop → main
        │
        ▼
GitHub Actions Pipeline
        │
        ├─ Secret Scan
        ├─ SAST Scan
        ├─ Dependency Scan
        ├─ Policy Check
        ├─ Build
        │
        ▼
If any job fails ❌
        │
        ▼
Merge blocked
8. Example Failed PR

GitHub shows:

❌ dependency-scan failed
❌ policy-check failed

Merge button becomes:

Merge blocked: checks failed
9. Optional Enterprise Rule

You can also require:

Require branches to be up to date before merging

This ensures:

develop branch
must be rebased with main
before merge
10. Git Workflow Example

Developer workflow:

Create feature branch

git checkout -b feature-login

Push code

git push origin feature-login

Create PR

feature-login → develop

After testing:

develop → main

Pipeline runs again.

✅ Recommended Enterprise Branch Strategy

main       → production
develop    → integration
feature/*  → new features
hotfix/*   → urgent fixes
